# 📘 MODULE EXPERIMENT 2 — FILE ORGANIZATION & DISK ALLOCATION

## 1.1 Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1.1 What is File Organization?

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Formal Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology):**
> *File Organization* refers to the logical method by which the records of a file are arranged on secondary storage (disk). It determines how data is **stored**, **retrieved**, **updated**, and **protected** by the Operating System. File organization encompasses two parallel concerns: (a) the **Directory Structure** (how files are *named* and *grouped*), and (b) the **Physical Allocation Strategy** (how file *blocks* are placed on disk).

> [!NOTE]
> **Why This Experiment Matters:**
> The OS must be able to locate a file by its **name** (Directory lookup) and then translate the logical byte offset into a physical disk address (Allocation strategy). Experiment 2 forces you to implement *both* layers — the name layer (Single/Multi-level directory) and the storage layer (Sequential/Linked/Indexed) — typically using `C` and a simulated file as a "virtual disk."

---

### 1.1.2 Directory Organization — Intuitive Analogy

Think of a **University Records Office**:

| Concept | Real-World Analogy | Computer Equivalent |
|---|---|---|
| Single-Level Directory | A **single large table** where every student's file is dumped. Names must be unique university-wide. | All file names in one root folder (`/`) — no two files can have the same name even if owned by different users. |
| Two-Level Directory | Each **Department** has its own cabinet; inside, students are filed. "Rahul" can exist in CSE *and* ECE. | A `Master File Directory (MFD)` pointing to one `User File Directory (UFD)` per user. |
| Tree-Structured (Multi-Level) Directory | The University has a **Cabinet → Department → Year → Section → Student** hierarchy. | The classic `/home/cse/s4/A/rollno.txt` Linux/Windows hierarchy. |
| Acyclic-Graph Directory | A student's academic record is **shared** in multiple sections (no duplicates physically). | Hard links / symbolic links — same inode referenced twice. |

> [!TIP]
> **KTU High-Yield Term:** A *Multi-Level Directory* is officially defined as a **hierarchical** structure in which each directory (except root) has exactly **one** parent, forming a **tree**. When **shared subdirectories** are allowed, it becomes an *Acyclic-Graph Directory*. A *General-Graph Directory* (which is **not** asked in the syllabus) permits cycles and is generally avoided.

---

### 1.1.3 Disk Allocation Strategy — Intuitive Analogy

Imagine a **hotel with 200 rooms** and a guest booking system:

- **Sequential Allocation** → The guest is given **rooms 47, 48, 49, 50** (contiguous block). Easy to find, but hard to extend.
- **Linked Allocation** → The guest's name is written on the **door of room 47**, pointing to room 112, then room 8, then room 199. The doors are chained. Order is preserved, but to find room 50 you must walk through 47→112→8→199.
- **Indexed Allocation** → The guest gets a **key-card at reception (index block)** that lists all assigned rooms: `{47, 112, 8, 199}`. Reception can jump directly to any room.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Core Definitions (KTU Exam Gold):**
> - **Sequential Allocation:** A file occupies a set of **contiguous blocks** on disk. The starting address and length are stored in the directory entry.
> - **Linked Allocation:** Each disk block contains the file's data *and* a **pointer to the next block**. The directory entry stores only the **starting block**.
> - **Indexed Allocation:** A special **index block** stores pointers to all the data blocks belonging to a file. The directory entry stores the **pointer to the index block**.

### 1.1.4 Standard Performance Metrics (Bold for Emphasis)

The three allocation strategies are routinely graded on these metrics in KTU papers:

- **External Fragmentation**
- **Internal Fragmentation**
- **Random Access Time (Seek)**
- **Sequential Access Throughput**

Each strategy will be benchmarked against these **four** parameters throughout Section 2.

---

