# 🧠 DEEP THEORETICAL ANALYSIS & KTU HIGH-YIELD FORMULA SHEET

## 2.1 Directory Organization — Detailed Operational Logic

### 2.1.1 Single-Level Directory

- **Structure:** All files of all users exist in **one flat list**.
- **Lookup:** Linear scan of the Master File Directory (MFD) for the file name.
- **Constraints:** File names must be **globally unique**.
- **Search Cost:** $O(n)$ where $n$ is total files in the system.
- **Sharing:** Not supported natively.
- **Drawback:** Two users cannot have a file with the same name — even if logically distinct.

**Step-by-step internal mechanics:**
1. User issues a system call `open("report.txt", O_RDONLY)`.
2. Kernel scans MFD entry-by-entry comparing strings.
3. If match is found → inode is returned to the process.
4. If no match → `-1` returned, `errno = ENOENT`.

### 2.1.2 Two-Level Directory

- **Structure:** One **MFD (Master File Directory)** + many **UFDs (User File Directories)**, one per user.
- **Lookup:** First locate the user's UFD via MFD using `username`, then scan UFD for the file name.
- **Search Cost:** $O(u + f)$ where $u$ is users, $f$ is files in user's UFD.
- **Path Specification:** Required prefix, e.g., `username:filename`.
- **Limitation:** A user **cannot** conveniently share or nest subdirectories.

### 2.1.3 Tree-Structured (Multi-Level) Directory

- **Structure:** A **root directory** at the top, with directories as nodes and files as leaves. A path is a sequence of names from root to target, separated by `/` (UNIX) or `\` (Windows).
- **Special Names:** `.` (current), `..` (parent).
- **Lookup:** Path-name resolution traverses the tree **left-to-right** (UNIX) or **right-to-left** (Windows — drives at start).
- **Search Cost (Average):** $O(d \cdot b)$ where $d$ is the depth of the path and $b$ is the average branching factor.
- **Operations Supported:** `mkdir`, `rmdir`, `chdir`, `link`, `unlink`.

### 2.1.4 Acyclic-Graph Directory

- **Structure:** Tree + **shared nodes** (links).
- **Implementation:** Two kinds of links — **Hard links** (multiple directory entries point to the *same inode*; a reference counter prevents premature deletion) and **Symbolic / Soft links** (a special file that *contains* the path name of the target; breaks if target is deleted).
- **Reference Counter Rule:**
$$\text{File is removed from disk} \iff \text{Reference Counter} = 0$$
- **Problem:** Cycles (a subdir links to its own ancestor) can cause infinite loops during traversal.

### 2.1.5 General-Graph Directory

- Same as Acyclic-Graph but **cycles allowed**.
- **Required for KTU awareness only** — must be handled by *garbage collection* or *reference counting with cycle detection*. **Not part of Module 2 implementation.**

---

## 2.2 Disk Allocation Strategies — Detailed Operational Logic

### 2.2.1 Sequential (Contiguous) Allocation

- **Mechanism:** A file of $n$ blocks is stored at blocks $b, b+1, b+2, \ldots, b+n-1$.
- **Directory Entry Holds:** `(starting_block_address, length_in_blocks)`.
- **Address Translation:** For a logical offset $k$ bytes, with block size $B$:
$$\text{Physical Block} = b + \left\lfloor \frac{k}{B} \right\rfloor$$
- **Pros:** Excellent **random access** (only 1 seek for any byte), highest **throughput** for sequential I/O.
- **Cons:** Suffers from **external fragmentation**; file size must be declared at creation; growing a file may require a full relocation.

### 2.2.2 Linked Allocation

- **Mechanism:** Each block holds a **pointer** (typically 4 bytes) to the next block. The last block's pointer is a sentinel value (e.g., `-1` or `NULL`).
- **Directory Entry Holds:** `(starting_block_address)` only.
- **Address Translation:** To reach block $i$, the OS must follow $i$ pointers from the start block → $\Theta(i)$ disk seeks.
- **FAT (File Allocation Table) Variant:** A table stored in memory holds *all* pointers, turning translation into $O(1)$ and making linked allocation practical (used in MS-DOS / Windows).
- **Pros:** No external fragmentation; simple to extend.
- **Cons:** Random access is slow without FAT; pointer overhead per block; reliability issue if a pointer is lost.

### 2.2.3 Indexed Allocation

- **Mechanism:** A dedicated **index block** is allocated for each file. The index block contains an array of pointers to all data blocks of the file.
- **Directory Entry Holds:** `(pointer_to_index_block)`.
- **Address Translation:** To reach block $i$ of the file → read the index block, look up the $i$-th pointer.
- **Multi-Level Indexed (UNIX `inode`):** Uses **direct blocks**, **single-indirect**, **double-indirect**, **triple-indirect** pointers to overcome the limit of one index block.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Block-Size Problem in Indexed Allocation:** A fixed index block can only address $N = \frac{B}{P}$ files, where $B$ is block size and $P$ is pointer size. With $B = 4096$ bytes and $P = 4$ bytes, $N = 1024$ blocks. Solution: combine with multi-level indexing (covered in OS theory modules — not in lab, but KTU asks it).

---

## 2.3 KTU Formula Sheet & Cheat-Sheet Table

> [!NOTE]
> Use this table as your **revision-1-page-sheet** before the lab viva. No vertical pipes are used inside cells — only `\vert` and `\cdot` notation to keep the markdown table intact.

| Parameter | Sequential | Linked | Indexed |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Directory Entry Fields** | `start_block, length` | `start_block` | `index_block_ptr` |
| **Random Access Time** | $O(1)$ — only 1 seek | $O(i)$ — seek $i$ blocks | $O(1)$ — 1 seek + memory read |
| **Sequential Throughput** | **Highest** (single seek, multi-block DMA) | Medium (seek per block) | Medium (seek per block) |
| **External Fragmentation** | **Yes — severe** | None | None |
| **Internal Fragmentation** | None (usually) | None (overhead per block) | Yes — partial index block unused |
| **File Size Limit** | Disk exhaustion | Disk exhaustion | $\vert \text{index block capacity} \vert$ |
| **Reliability** | High (no pointers to corrupt) | Low (one bad pointer = data loss) | Medium (index block is single point of failure) |
| **Typical Use** | CD-ROM, DVD, archival tapes | FAT / NTFS (with table) | UNIX `inode`, NTFS MFT |
| **Formula — Max File Size** | $L_{\max} = N \cdot B$ | $L_{\max} = N \cdot (B - P)$ | $L_{\max} = N \cdot B$ where $N = B \div P$ |
| **Fragmentation Type** | External | None (pointer overhead is internal per block) | Internal (partial index) |

**Legend:** $B$ = block size (bytes), $P$ = pointer size (bytes), $N$ = number of blocks addressable, $L_{\max}$ = maximum file size, $i$ = block index being accessed.

### 2.4 Why Does This Matter in Industry?

- **Databases (PostgreSQL, Oracle)** still use *contiguous* allocation patterns through tablespaces and clustered indexes for sequential scan speed.
- **NTFS (Windows)** uses a refined indexed approach — the **MFT (Master File Table)** stores file metadata + small files *inline*, and uses **runs** (contiguous extents) within the B-Tree data structure.
- **ext4 / XFS (Linux)** use a hybrid: block groups with **indexed allocation** for metadata and a **delayed-allocation** strategy to choose contiguous extents.
- **Solid-State Drives (SSDs)** reduce the importance of seek time, but the *write amplification* problem makes sequential allocation still preferred for hot files.

---

