# 🧮 STEP-BY-STEP DERIVATIONS, ANALYTICAL MATRIX & SAMPLE C-IMPLEMENTATION

## 3.1 Analytic Derivation of Max File Size

**Given:**
- Block size $B = 4096$ bytes
- Pointer size $P = 4$ bytes
- Disk has $D = 2^{32}$ addressable blocks

**Derivation (for Indexed Allocation):**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Pointers per index block } N &= \frac{B}{P} \\
&= \frac{4096 \text{ bytes}}{4 \text{ bytes per pointer}} \\
&= 1024 \text{ pointers}
\end{aligned}
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Maximum file size } L_{\max} &= N \cdot B \\
&= 1024 \times 4096 \\
&= 2^{10} \times 2^{12} \\
&= 2^{22} \text{ bytes} \\
&= 4 \text{ MiB}
\end{aligned}
$$

**Row 1 (logic):** The index block occupies exactly one disk block of size $B$. Each pointer consumes $P$ bytes. So the number of file blocks the index can address is the block size divided by pointer size.

**Row 2 (logic):** Maximum file size equals the number of addressable blocks multiplied by block size. Each block contributes $B$ bytes of file data.

**Row 3 (logic):** Substituting the numbers gives $2^{10} \times 2^{12} = 2^{22} = 4 \text{ MiB}$.

> [!NOTE]
> **Conclusion:** A *single-level* indexed allocation with 4-byte pointers and 4 KiB blocks caps a file at 4 MiB. UNIX breaks this limit by chaining a **double-indirect** block that points to other index blocks. This is why `inode` in Linux can address **terabytes** of data.

---

## 3.2 Worked Example — Contiguous Allocation Address Translation

**File `F` starts at block 17, length = 5 blocks, block size = 1024 bytes.**
**Process requests a read at byte offset 2500.**

**Derivation:**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Block number within file} &= \left\lfloor \frac{\text{byte offset}}{B} \right\rfloor \\
&= \left\lfloor \frac{2500}{1024} \right\rfloor \\
&= \lfloor 2.44 \rfloor \\
&= 2 \text{ (0-indexed)}
\end{aligned}
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Physical block on disk} &= \text{start\_block} + \text{block within file} \\
&= 17 + 2 \\
&= 19
\end{aligned}
$$

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Offset within physical block} &= 2500 \bmod 1024 \\
&= 2500 - 2 \times 1024 \\
&= 2500 - 2048 \\
&= 452 \text{ bytes}
\end{aligned}
$$

**Reading logic:** The disk head moves to block 19, waits for the platter to rotate so byte 452 is under the read head, then transfers bytes 452 → 1023 of that block (572 bytes — the request may span into block 20 as well).

---

## 3.3 Analytical Matrix — Choosing the Best Strategy (KTU Favourite Question)

| Use-Case | Best Strategy | Reasoning |
|---|---|---|
| CD-ROM ISO image distribution | **Sequential** | Read-only, no fragmentation issues, fastest streaming. |
| Log file appending on Linux | **Linked** (via FAT) | Append = add to end, no relocation, no external frag. |
| Random-access database file (B-Tree) | **Indexed** | $O(1)$ random access to any page is mandatory. |
| Multimedia streaming (large movie) | **Sequential** (with extent) | Highest throughput, predictable seek. |
| Virtual memory swap file | **Indexed** | Kernel needs to access any page instantly. |
| Small config files (< 4 KiB) | **Indexed** (with inline storage) | Whole file fits inside the index block. |

---

## 3.4 Sample C-Implementation (Reference Algorithm for Lab Record)

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The KTU lab record must include a working C program. The following snippets show the *minimal algorithmic skeleton* the examiner expects. You may extend it to a complete menu-driven program. All file names use `FILE *fp` from `<stdio.h>`.

### 3.4.1 Simulated Disk Block (Common to All Strategies)

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>

#define BLOCK_SIZE   512
#define DISK_BLOCKS  1024
#define MAX_FILES    50
#define MAX_NAME     30

/* A simulated "disk" — an array of fixed-size blocks stored in memory */
typedef struct {
    char data[BLOCK_SIZE];
} DiskBlock;

DiskBlock disk[DISK_BLOCKS];

/* A bitmap to mark which blocks are free (1 = used, 0 = free) */
int block_status[DISK_BLOCKS] = {0};
```

### 3.4.2 Single-Level Directory Entry

```c
typedef struct {
    char fname[MAX_NAME];           /* file name */
    int  start_block;               /* starting physical block */
    int  num_blocks;                /* number of blocks */
} DirectoryEntry;

DirectoryEntry MFD[MAX_FILES];      /* Master File Directory */
int file_count = 0;
```

### 3.4.3 Sequential Allocation Functions

```c
int find_contiguous(int n) {
    int free_run = 0, start = -1;
    for (int i = 0; i < DISK_BLOCKS; i++) {
        if (block_status[i] == 0) {
            if (free_run == 0) start = i;
            free_run++;
            if (free_run == n) return start;
        } else {
            free_run = 0;
        }
    }
    return -1;   /* not enough contiguous space */
}

void create_file_seq(char *name, int size_in_blocks) {
    int start = find_contiguous(size_in_blocks);
    if (start == -1) {
        printf("Error: Not enough contiguous space (external fragmentation).\n");
        return;
    }
    for (int i = 0; i < size_in_blocks; i++) block_status[start + i] = 1;
    strcpy(MFD[file_count].fname, name);
    MFD[file_count].start_block = start;
    MFD[file_count].num_blocks = size_in_blocks;
    file_count++;
    printf("Sequential file '%s' created. Starts at block %d.\n", name, start);
}
```

### 3.4.4 Linked Allocation — Modified Block Structure

```c
typedef struct {
    char data[BLOCK_SIZE - sizeof(int)];
    int  next;                      /* -1 = end of file */
} LinkedBlock;
```

```c
void create_file_linked(char *name, int size_in_blocks) {
    int prev = -1, first = -1;
    for (int k = 0; k < size_in_blocks; k++) {
        int b;
        for (b = 0; b < DISK_BLOCKS; b++) if (block_status[b] == 0) break;
        if (b == DISK_BLOCKS) { printf("Disk full.\n"); return; }
        block_status[b] = 1;
        ((LinkedBlock*)&disk[b])->next = -1;
        if (k == 0) first = b; else ((LinkedBlock*)&disk[prev])->next = b;
        prev = b;
    }
    strcpy(MFD[file_count].fname, name);
    MFD[file_count].start_block = first;
    MFD[file_count].num_blocks  = size_in_blocks;
    file_count++;
    printf("Linked file '%s' created. Starts at block %d.\n", name, first);
}
```

### 3.4.5 Indexed Allocation

```c
typedef struct {
    int  pointers[BLOCK_SIZE / sizeof(int)];
} IndexBlock;
```

```c
void create_file_indexed(char *name, int size_in_blocks) {
    /* 1. allocate index block */
    int idx;
    for (idx = 0; idx < DISK_BLOCKS; idx++) if (block_status[idx] == 0) break;
    block_status[idx] = 1;
    IndexBlock *ib = (IndexBlock *)&disk[idx];

    /* 2. allocate data blocks, register pointers */
    int k;
    for (k = 0; k < size_in_blocks; k++) {
        int b;
        for (b = 0; b < DISK_BLOCKS; b++) if (block_status[b] == 0) break;
        if (b == DISK_BLOCKS) { printf("Disk full.\n"); return; }
        block_status[b] = 1;
        ib->pointers[k] = b;
    }
    ib->pointers[k] = -1;       /* sentinel */
    strcpy(MFD[file_count].fname, name);
    MFD[file_count].start_block = idx;       /* points to INDEX block */
    MFD[file_count].num_blocks  = size_in_blocks;
    file_count++;
    printf("Indexed file '%s' created. Index block at %d.\n", name, idx);
}
```

### 3.4.6 Multi-Level Directory (User Folders)

```c
typedef struct {
    char uname[MAX_NAME];
    DirectoryEntry ufd[MAX_FILES];  /* per-user file directory */
    int  ufd_count;
} UserDir;

UserDir users[20];
int user_count = 0;

int find_user(char *uname) {
    for (int i = 0; i < user_count; i++)
        if (strcmp(users[i].uname, uname) == 0) return i;
    return -1;
}
```

The complete menu-driven program should have options: `1) Create User`, `2) Create File (Sequential/Linked/Indexed)`, `3) Display Directory`, `4) Delete File`, `5) Exit`. This is the **minimum expectation** for a 14-mark lab record answer.

---

## 3.5 Complexity Derivation Table

| Operation | Single-Level | Multi-Level (Tree) | Seq Alloc | Linked Alloc | Indexed Alloc |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| Create File | $O(n)$ (scan MFD) | $O(d)$ (walk path) | $O(n)$ to find contiguous run | $O(n \cdot b)$ | $O(n \cdot b)$ |
| Delete File | $O(n)$ | $O(d)$ | $O(n)$ mark free | $O(n)$ walk chain | $O(n)$ free data + index |
| Search File | $O(n)$ | $O(d \cdot b)$ | — | — | — |
| Read Block $i$ | — | — | $O(1)$ | $O(i)$ (no FAT) / $O(1)$ (with FAT) | $O(1)$ |
| Write Append | — | — | may fail / relocate | $O(1)$ find free + link | $O(1)$ add to index |

Here $n$ = total entries, $b$ = blocks, $d$ = directory depth.

---

