### **Question B (14 Marks) — `[KTU University Exam - May 2023]`**

**(a)** Explain **Linked Allocation** and **Indexed Allocation** with diagrams. Compare their **random access** performance. **(7 Marks)**

**(b)** Write a C program that implements a **Two-Level Directory** supporting per-user file creation, listing, and deletion. Show the data structure and the `create_file_in_user()` function. **(7 Marks)**

---

#### **Model Solution (a) — 7 Marks**

**Linked Allocation (3 marks):**
- Each block contains a **data portion** and a **pointer to the next block**; the directory entry holds only the starting block.
- **Random Access:** To access the $i$-th block, the OS starts at the first block and follows $i-1$ pointers — so access time is $O(i)$, i.e., proportional to the block's position. Without a FAT, this is slow.
- **With FAT (File Allocation Table):** The whole chain is cached in memory, so random access becomes $O(1)$.
- **Disadvantage:** Pointer overhead in every block; a single bad pointer corrupts the rest of the file.

**Indexed Allocation (3 marks):**
- A dedicated **index block** contains an array of pointers to the data blocks of the file. Directory entry holds a single pointer to the index block.
- **Random Access:** Read the index block into memory → access pointer $i$ → read the data block. Time is $O(1)$ (one disk seek for index + one for data).
- **Limit:** A single index block caps file size at $N \cdot B$ where $N = B / P$ (e.g., 4 MiB for 4 KiB blocks, 4-byte pointers).
- **Solution:** Multi-level indexed (UNIX `inode`).

**Comparison table (1 mark):**
- Linked: $O(i)$ random access (no FAT), $O(1)$ with FAT; wastes pointer space per block.
- Indexed: $O(1)$ random access always; wastes space in sparse index.

(Diagrams already covered in §4.5 and §4.6 — re-use them in the answer sheet.)

