#### **Model Solution (b) — 7 Marks**

**Data Structure (2 marks):**
```c
#define MAX_USERS 10
#define MAX_FILES 20
typedef struct {
    char fname[30];
    int  start_block;
    int  num_blocks;
} DirEntry;

typedef struct {
    char uname[20];
    DirEntry ufd[MAX_FILES];
    int  file_count;
} User;

User MFD[MAX_USERS];
int user_count = 0;
```

**Helper to find a user (1 mark):**
```c
int find_user(char *u) {
    for (int i = 0; i < user_count; i++)
        if (strcmp(MFD[i].uname, u) == 0) return i;
    return -1;
}
```

**`create_file_in_user()` (3 marks):**
```c
void create_file_in_user(char *u, char *fname, int size) {
    int uid = find_user(u);
    if (uid == -1) { printf("User %s not found.\n", u); return; }
    if (MFD[uid].file_count >= MAX_FILES) { printf("UFD full.\n"); return; }
    int start = find_contiguous(size);
    if (start == -1) { printf("Disk full.\n"); return; }
    for (int i = 0; i < size; i++) block_status[start + i] = 1;
    int fc = MFD[uid].file_count;
    strcpy(MFD[uid].ufd[fc].fname, fname);
    MFD[uid].ufd[fc].start_block = start;
    MFD[uid].ufd[fc].num_blocks  = size;
    MFD[uid].file_count++;
    printf("File '%s' created in UFD of user '%s'.\n", fname, u);
}
```

**Explaination (1 mark):** This is a *Two-Level* directory because there is one MFD listing users, and each user has a private UFD listing files. File names are unique only within a user's UFD — two users may have a file called `notes.txt`.

