> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Common Pitfalls**
> 1. **Confusing *Logical* Directory with *Physical* Allocation.** Many students mix up the two and answer "Single-Level vs Sequential" as if they are comparable. They are **orthogonal** concepts — single-level/multi-level is the *name space*, sequential/linked/indexed is the *disk layout*. Always clarify the distinction in your first paragraph.
> 2. **Forgetting the FAT variant of Linked Allocation.** If the examiner asks for the **drawback** of linked allocation, mentioning "$O(i)$ random access" *and* "the FAT solves this" shows depth and earns 1 extra mark.
> 3. **In C-program answers, missing the bitmap / free-block tracking.** A program that allocates blocks but never marks `block_status[]` is functionally incorrect — the next `create_file` will overwrite existing data. Always include the bitmap.
> 4. **Off-by-one errors in address translation.** Byte offset 2500 in a 1024-byte block is **block 2 (0-indexed)**, not block 3. Examiners deliberately give tricky numbers to test this.
> 5. **Diagrams without labels.** A box labelled "MFD" with no arrows showing `start_block → disk` loses 1–2 marks. Always label arrows.
> 6. **Forgetting to mention UNIX `inode` is multi-level indexed.** Saying "UNIX uses indexed allocation" is incomplete — it uses **multi-level indexed** (direct, single-indirect, double-indirect, triple-indirect). This single keyword can be the difference between 7/7 and 6/7.

