## 5.3 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember (Rapid-Revision Checklist)

- [x] **File Organization** = Directory Structure (name layer) + Allocation Strategy (storage layer).
- [x] **Single-Level Directory**: one MFD, global uniqueness, no sharing, $O(N)$ search.
- [x] **Two-Level Directory**: MFD + per-user UFD; path is `user:file`; still no sub-folders.
- [x] **Multi-Level / Tree Directory**: hierarchical, path-based, supports `mkdir/rmdir`; no cycles.
- [x] **Acyclic-Graph Directory**: tree + hard/sym links; reference counter governs deletion; **no cycles**.
- [x] **Sequential Allocation**: contiguous blocks, directory stores `start, length`; **external fragmentation**; best for **CD/DVD** and large streaming.
- [x] **Linked Allocation**: chain of blocks; directory stores `start` only; **no external frag**; **FAT** gives $O(1)$ random access; worst case without FAT is $O(i)$.
- [x] **Indexed Allocation**: index block holds pointers; **$O(1)$ random access**; file size cap $N \cdot B = (B \div P) \cdot B$; UNIX `inode` extends with multi-level indexing.
- [x] **Fragmentation**: external in sequential; pointer-overhead "internal" in linked; index-block internal in indexed.
